questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alluri Sitarama Raju&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alluri Sitarama Raju was a prominent Indian revolutionary who led the tribal revolt known as the &lt;strong&gt;Rampa Rebellion of 1922&lt;/strong&gt; against British colonial rule.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The rebellion was primarily against oppressive &lt;strong&gt;forest laws&lt;/strong&gt; imposed by the British, which restricted the access of tribal communities to their traditional forest resources.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Raju organized the tribal people in the region of &lt;strong&gt;Godavari Agency&lt;/strong&gt; (present-day Andhra Pradesh) and initiated guerrilla warfare against British forces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He is remembered for his courage and leadership and was referred to as &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Manyam Veerudu&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (Hero of the Jungle) by locals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Raju was eventually captured and executed by the British in &lt;strong&gt;1924&lt;/strong&gt;, making him a martyr in India&amp;rsquo;s struggle for independence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rampa Rebellion:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Rampa Rebellion was also known as the &lt;strong&gt;Rampa Uprising&lt;/strong&gt;, which occurred between &lt;strong&gt;1922-1924&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The tribal communities revolted against colonial policies that restricted their rights to cultivate podu lands (shifting cultivation) and access forest resources.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was one of the significant tribal movements in India&amp;rsquo;s freedom struggle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact of Forest Laws:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Indian Forest Act of 1927&lt;/strong&gt; imposed stringent regulations on the use of forest resources, severely affecting tribal livelihoods.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These laws restricted activities like grazing cattle, collecting firewood, and hunting, leading to widespread resentment among the tribal population.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guerrilla Warfare:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alluri Sitarama Raju adopted guerrilla tactics, using the dense forests of Andhra Pradesh for ambushes and surprise attacks on British forces.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;His revolutionary methods inspired several other freedom fighters and tribal movements across India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Legacy:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alluri Sitarama Raju remains a celebrated figure in Indian history, especially in Andhra Pradesh, where his contributions are commemorated through statues and educational institutions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Government of India has also issued postal stamps in his honor.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The limit of CO2 emissions to meet climate goals&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon Budget&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the total amount of &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide (CO2)&lt;/strong&gt; emissions permitted over a specific time period to limit global temperature rise to a specific target, such as &lt;strong&gt;1.5°C or 2°C above pre-industrial levels&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;The concept is derived from the &lt;strong&gt;Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC)&lt;/strong&gt; reports, which provide scientific assessments of the remaining carbon budget to avoid catastrophic climate impacts.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;It is crucial to achieving the goals of the &lt;strong&gt;Paris Agreement&lt;/strong&gt;, which aims to limit global warming to well below 2°C, preferably to 1.5°C.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;The carbon budget includes emissions from all sources, such as &lt;strong&gt;fossil fuel combustion, deforestation, and industrial processes&lt;/strong&gt;, and is measured in gigatons of CO2 (GtCO2).&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;Staying within the carbon budget requires transitioning to &lt;strong&gt;low-carbon energy systems, enhancing energy efficiency, and adopting sustainable land-use practices&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Components of Carbon Budget:&lt;/strong&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Historical Emissions:&lt;/strong&gt; Emissions already released into the atmosphere since the industrial revolution, contributing to global warming.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Remaining Carbon Budget:&lt;/strong&gt; The amount of CO2 that can still be emitted while limiting temperature rise to the target levels.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Non-CO2 Emissions:&lt;/strong&gt; Methane (CH4) and nitrous oxide (N2O) emissions also contribute to global warming and are considered in broader climate budgets.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Paris Agreement:&lt;/strong&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;Adopted in &lt;strong&gt;2015&lt;/strong&gt;, it is a legally binding international treaty involving &lt;strong&gt;196 countries&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;Aims to achieve a balance between emissions and removals by &lt;strong&gt;mid-century&lt;/strong&gt; to limit global temperature rise.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;Encourages nations to submit &lt;strong&gt;Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs)&lt;/strong&gt; outlining their climate action plans.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IPCC Reports:&lt;/strong&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;IPCC Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5°C&lt;/strong&gt; highlights that limiting warming to 1.5°C requires cutting global emissions by approximately &lt;strong&gt;45% by 2030&lt;/strong&gt; and achieving &lt;strong&gt;net-zero emissions by 2050&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;It emphasizes the importance of reducing emissions from sectors such as &lt;strong&gt;energy, agriculture, and transportation&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Strategies to Stay Within the Carbon Budget:&lt;/strong&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Renewable Energy:&lt;/strong&gt; Transitioning to solar, wind, and hydroelectric power to reduce dependence on fossil fuels.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy Efficiency:&lt;/strong&gt; Improving energy use in industries, buildings, and transportation systems.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon Sequestration:&lt;/strong&gt; Enhancing natural carbon sinks like forests and adopting technologies like &lt;strong&gt;Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Policy Measures:&lt;/strong&gt; Implementing carbon pricing, emission trading systems, and stricter regulations on greenhouse gas emissions.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Global Progress:&lt;/strong&gt; 
&lt;ul&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;As of &lt;strong&gt;2023&lt;/strong&gt;, several countries, including &lt;strong&gt;European Union nations, the US, and China&lt;/strong&gt;, have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by &lt;strong&gt;2050 or 2060&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;li&gt;Developing nations are also focusing on sustainable development pathways through international support and financing mechanisms.&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt; 
&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt;

