&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The latitude and altitude of the region&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Latitude:&lt;/strong&gt; Latitude is one of the primary factors that influence the climate of a region. The position of a region relative to the equator determines the amount of sunlight it receives, which in turn affects its temperature. Regions closer to the equator experience warmer climates, while those farther away experience cooler climates.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Altitude:&lt;/strong&gt; Altitude, or the height above sea level, significantly impacts the climate. Higher altitudes generally have cooler temperatures due to lower air pressure and density, and the temperature decreases by approximately 6.5&amp;deg;C for every 1,000 meters increase in altitude. For instance, mountainous regions are colder compared to areas at sea level. Hence, the altitude of a region plays a crucial role in determining its climate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Combination of Latitude and Altitude:&lt;/strong&gt; Together, latitude and altitude work to shape the climate of a region. For example, regions at high latitudes may have colder climates, but those at high altitudes in tropical regions may also experience cooler temperatures. This combination makes latitude and altitude the most influential factors in determining climate. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;quot;The latitude and altitude of the region.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Factors Influencing Climate:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Latitude:&lt;/strong&gt; It determines the intensity and duration of sunlight received in a region. For example, tropical regions near the equator receive direct sunlight throughout the year, resulting in warmer climates. On the other hand, polar regions receive less sunlight, leading to colder climates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Altitude:&lt;/strong&gt; Higher altitudes experience cooler temperatures. For instance, the Himalayas in India have a cold climate due to their high altitude, despite being located in a relatively warm region.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vegetation:&lt;/strong&gt; While vegetation affects microclimates and local temperatures, it does not significantly influence the broader climate of a region.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Longitude:&lt;/strong&gt; Longitude primarily affects the time zone and has minimal impact on climate. It does not influence factors like temperature or precipitation directly.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Population Density:&lt;/strong&gt; While human activities can influence local climates (e.g., urban heat islands), population density is not a major factor in determining the overall climate of a region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Latitude and Altitude Influence:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Equator:&lt;/strong&gt; Countries near the equator, such as &lt;strong&gt;Indonesia&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Brazil&lt;/strong&gt;, experience tropical climates with high temperatures and abundant rainfall.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mountainous Regions:&lt;/strong&gt; Areas like the &lt;strong&gt;Swiss Alps&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;strong&gt;Himalayas&lt;/strong&gt; have cooler climates due to their high altitude.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3729&quot; data-start=&quot;3585&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Polar Regions:&lt;/strong&gt; Areas near the poles, such as &lt;strong&gt;Antarctica&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;strong&gt;Arctic Circle&lt;/strong&gt;, experience extremely cold climates due to their high latitude.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Characteristics of Latitude:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tropical Zone:&lt;/strong&gt; Located between the &lt;strong&gt;Tropic of Cancer&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;strong&gt;Tropic of Capricorn&lt;/strong&gt;, this zone experiences warm climates year-round.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Polar Zone:&lt;/strong&gt; Located near the &lt;strong&gt;North Pole&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;South Pole&lt;/strong&gt;, this zone has extreme cold and ice-covered landscapes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Altitude and Its Effects:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Temperature Drop:&lt;/strong&gt; Temperature decreases as altitude increases, which is why mountainous regions are cooler.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Atmospheric Pressure:&lt;/strong&gt; Air pressure decreases at higher altitudes, affecting weather patterns and living conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Misconceptions about Other Factors:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5449&quot; data-start=&quot;5264&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vegetation:&lt;/strong&gt; While it can moderate local temperatures, it does not have a significant impact on regional or global climate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5630&quot; data-start=&quot;5454&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Population Density:&lt;/strong&gt; Human activities can create localized climate effects, such as urban heat islands, but do not determine the overall climate of a region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Background&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Initiated by Mahatma Gandhi after:&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Jallianwala Bagh Massacre (1919)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rowlatt Act (1919) &amp;ndash; Allowed arrest without trial&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Khilafat Movement (support to Ottoman Caliph) &amp;ndash; Muslims protested British actions in Turkey&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Official Launch&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Date: August 1, 1920&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Decision taken in Congress Session at Calcutta (September 1920) and confirmed at Nagpur Session (December 1920).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gandhiji&amp;rsquo;s call: &amp;quot;Swaraj in a year&amp;quot; through non-violent means.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Objectives&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Demand Swaraj (Self-rule)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Protest against:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rowlatt Act&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jallianwala Bagh massacre&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;British economic and political exploitation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Injustice to Khilafat cause&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Main Features&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boycott of British institutions:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Titles (e.g. knighthood)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Government schools and colleges&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Courts and legislature (e.g. boycott of elections under Montagu-Chelmsford reforms)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Foreign goods (especially cloth)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Civil services, police, army (resignation encouraged&lt;/strong&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Promotion of&lt;/strong&gt;:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Khadi and Indian handicrafts&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;National schools and colleges&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Panchayats and village industries&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Participation&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mass movement: First time peasants, students, workers, women joined in large numbers&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Major support in: Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Bengal, Punjab, Maharashtra&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Leaders involved: C.R. Das, Motilal Nehru, Jawaharlal Nehru, Ali Brothers (Shaukat &amp;amp; Mohammad Ali)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Events&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chauri Chaura Incident (February 5, 1922):&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Protest turned violent; a mob set a police station on fire, killing 22 policemen in Gorakhpur, UP.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gandhiji, a staunch supporter of non-violence, suspended the movement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Chambal Sanctuary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Chambal&amp;nbsp;Sanctuary,&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;also&amp;nbsp;called the&lt;strong&gt; National Chambal&amp;nbsp;Gharial Wildlife Sanctuary&lt;/strong&gt;, is a&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;tri-state protected area in northern India&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;home to&amp;nbsp;critically endangered gharial&amp;nbsp;(small crocodiles), the&amp;nbsp;red-crowned roof turtle, and the endangered Ganges river dolphin.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Within the sanctuary, the pristine&lt;strong&gt; Chambal River &lt;/strong&gt;cuts through edges of ravines and hills with many sandy beaches protected under &lt;strong&gt;India&amp;#39;s Wildlife Protection Act of 1972.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bhadra Wildlife Sanctuary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Bhadra wildlife sanctuary is located in &lt;strong&gt;Karnataka.&lt;/strong&gt; It is&amp;nbsp;a renowned&lt;strong&gt; tiger reserve with 33 tigers &lt;/strong&gt;inhabiting its periphery.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dandeli Wildlife Sanctuary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;The Dandeli wildlife sanctuary is the&lt;strong&gt; second largest sanctuary in Karnataka &lt;/strong&gt;and is located on the &lt;strong&gt;banks of River Kali.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary&amp;nbsp;is one of the &lt;strong&gt;13 sanctuaries&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;in the protected areas of the &lt;strong&gt;state of Kerala. &lt;/strong&gt;It&amp;nbsp;is home to the Great &lt;strong&gt;Grizzled Squirrel of India.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chotanagpur plateau&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Chotanagpur Plateau&lt;/strong&gt;, located in eastern India, specifically in Jharkhand, is rich in mineral resources, including iron ore, coal, and bauxite, making it the hub for iron and steel industries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Prominent iron and steel plants such as &lt;strong&gt;Tata Steel (Jamshedpur)&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Bokaro Steel Plant&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;Rourkela Steel Plant&lt;/strong&gt; are situated in and around this region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The availability of high-grade iron ore and coal in close proximity ensures lower transportation costs and efficient production processes for steel manufacturing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This plateau is also strategically located near major rivers such as Damodar and Subarnarekha, ensuring water supply for industrial operations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chotanagpur&amp;rsquo;s mineral-rich geology and infrastructure contribute to it being the backbone of India&amp;#39;s iron and steel industry.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron Ore:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;India is one of the leading producers of iron ore globally, with deposits found mainly in Odisha, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Karnataka, and Goa.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Iron ore is the primary raw material used in steel production, accounting for 98% of mined iron globally.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Damodar Valley Corporation (DVC):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established in 1948, DVC serves as a critical source of power and water supply for industries in the Chotanagpur Plateau.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its thermal power plants are key contributors to the industrial energy needs of the region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tata Steel:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Founded in 1907, Tata Steel&amp;#39;s Jamshedpur plant is India&amp;rsquo;s oldest steel manufacturing facility and is located in the Chotanagpur Plateau.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It played a pivotal role in the industrialization of India and continues to be a global leader in steel production.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Steel Industry in India:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;India is the second-largest producer of steel globally, with a production capacity exceeding 120 million tonnes annually.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The iron and steel industry is crucial to India&amp;#39;s economy, contributing significantly to infrastructure development, manufacturing, and exports.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Manmohan Singh&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LPG model&lt;/strong&gt; of development was introduced in&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;1991&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Finance minister from &lt;strong&gt;1991-1996&lt;/strong&gt; was&amp;nbsp;Dr. Manmohan Singh.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence the correct answer is Dr. Manmohan Singh&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LPG Model:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;India&amp;rsquo;s &lt;strong&gt;New Economic Policy&lt;/strong&gt; was announced &lt;strong&gt;on July 24, 1991&lt;/strong&gt;, which is popularly known as the LPG reforms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LPG means Liberalisation, Privatisation, and Globalisation model&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Liberalization- &lt;/strong&gt;It refers to the process of making policies that are&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;less constraining&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;economic activity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Privatization- &lt;/strong&gt;It refers to the&lt;strong&gt; transfer of ownership &lt;/strong&gt;of property or business from a government to a privately owned entity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Globalization-&lt;/strong&gt; It refers to the &lt;strong&gt;expansion of economic activities&lt;/strong&gt; across &lt;strong&gt;political boundaries&lt;/strong&gt; of nation-states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Salient features of LPG Policy:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Abolition of Industrial licensing/ Permit Raj.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Diluted role of the public sector enterprises.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Beginning of privatization.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Free entry to foreign investment and technology.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Reduction in import tariffs.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Deregulation of markets.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Reduction of taxes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P. T. Usha.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P. T Usha is a retired Indian track and field athlete.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She has won&lt;strong&gt; 4 Asian gold medals and 7 Silver medals.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She is often called the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Queen of Indian track and field&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On 6 July 2022, she was&lt;strong&gt; nominated to the Rajya Sabha &lt;/strong&gt;by President Ram Nath Kovind.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She is also nicknamed &lt;strong&gt;Golden Girl.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Prad&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;ip Kumar Banerjee&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pradip Kumar Banerjee was an Indian professional footballer who played as a striker for the Indian national football team.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He was one of the first recipients of the Arjuna Award when the awards were instituted in 1961.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Milkha Singh&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Milkha Singh also known as&lt;strong&gt; The Flying Sikh&lt;/strong&gt;, was an Indian track and field sprinter.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He is the &lt;strong&gt;only athlete to win gold in 400 meters&lt;/strong&gt; at the Asian Games as well as the Commonwealth Games.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hima Das&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hima Das, nicknamed Dhing Express, is an Indian sprinter from the state of Assam.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She is the first Indian athlete to win a gold medal in a track event at the IAAF World U20 Championships.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Qutbuddin Aibak&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Qutub Minar&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Qutub-Minar in red and buff sandstone is the highest tower in India.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It has been declared as a UNESCO world heritage site.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The construction of the Qutub Minar was started by Qutub-ud-Din Aibak and was completed by Iltutmish.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8cb4d073-7fff-fb96-88da-707d81e953ae&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;cke_bm_12695S&quot; style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;Qutab Minar is a soaring, 73 m-high tower of victory, built-in 1193 by Qutab-ud-din Aibak immediately after the defeat of Delhi&amp;#39;s last Hindu kingdom&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8cb4d073-7fff-fb96-88da-707d81e953ae&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The tower has five distinct stories.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8cb4d073-7fff-fb96-88da-707d81e953ae&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The first three storeys are made of red sandstone; the fourth and fifth storeys are of marble and sandstone.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Qutab-ud-din Aibak&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Qutab-ud-din Aibak was the first Muslim ruler of Delhi, ruled from 1206 to 1210 AD.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He was considered the real founder of the Delhi sultanate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He constructed Quwwat-ul-Islam mosque in Delhi and Adhai Din Ka Jhonpra in Ajmer.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He initiated the construction of Qutb Minar and was completed by Iltutmish.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Akbar (1556-1605)&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Emperor Akbar founded the city in by the name of &amp;ldquo;ILLAHABAS&amp;rdquo; which later became ALLAHABAD.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He introduced the new religion as Din Ilahi.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He introduced the Mansabdari system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Akbar defeated Hemu in the second battle of Panipat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He built Ibadat Khana in Fatehpur Sikri.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He followed the policy of Sulh-i-kul.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Shah Jahan (1627-1658)&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He was the son of Jahangir.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;A French traveller, Tavernier visited during his reign&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Diwan-i-Khas and Diwan-i-Am, a hall of private and public audiences are built by Shahjahan.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Khizr Khan&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He was the first Sayyid dynasty ruler who ruled Delhi from 1414-1421.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He was the founder of the Sayyid dynasty.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He was succeeded by his son Mubarak Shah.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;span id=&quot;cke_bm_13335E&quot; style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct Answer is Option &lt;strong&gt;3&lt;/strong&gt; i.e &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Parliament&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parliament is the final authority for making laws in India.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law proposals which are passed by the parliament should be &lt;strong&gt;approved by the President&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And similarly, the law proposals which are passed by state legislatures should be &lt;strong&gt;approved by Governor&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Parliament has also the power to amend the laws in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prime Minister&lt;/strong&gt; is the head of the &lt;strong&gt;council of ministers&lt;/strong&gt; and also &lt;strong&gt;head the cabinet&lt;/strong&gt; and acts as the chief advisor to the President.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Liberalisation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Liberalisation&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the removal or reduction of restrictions or barriers on free exchange of goods, services, and capital between nations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It became a significant outcome of globalisation as countries adopted policies that reduced government control over the economy and encouraged private enterprise.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In India, liberalisation was initiated in 1991 as part of economic reforms aimed at integrating the Indian economy with the global economy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Liberalisation facilitates &lt;strong&gt;foreign direct investment (FDI)&lt;/strong&gt;, trade liberalisation, and technological advancements, fostering economic growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It encourages competition, improves efficiency, and provides consumers with better goods and services at competitive prices.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Outsourcing:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Outsourcing involves contracting out business processes or services to third-party providers, often in another country, due to cost efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a key feature of globalisation as it allows companies to access global talent and reduce operational costs.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include IT services, customer support, and manufacturing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While outsourcing is a result of globalisation, it is not the primary outcome of the process.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Capitalisation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Capitalisation refers to the financial structure of a company or economy, often involving investment in assets and equity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is an economic concept that is influenced by globalisation but is not a direct outcome of it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Capitalisation determines the financial capacity of businesses to expand and operate efficiently in a competitive market.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Privatisation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Privatisation is the process of transferring ownership of a business, enterprise, or public service from the government to private entities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It encourages efficiency, competition, and investment by reducing government monopoly in various sectors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Though privatisation is often a part of liberalisation policies, it is not the overarching outcome of globalisation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Main Theme:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Globalisation refers to the process of increased interconnectedness and interdependence of economies, societies, and cultures across the world.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its major outcomes include liberalisation, the spread of technology, economic integration, and cultural exchange.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These outcomes lead to improved global trade, innovation, and economic development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tamil Nadu.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kudanukulam Nuclear Power Station is located in&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tamil Nadu.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kudanukulam Nuclear Power Station is the &lt;strong&gt;largest nuclear power plant in India.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is situated in the &lt;strong&gt;Tirunelveli district&lt;/strong&gt; of Tamil Nadu.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was built in collaboration with Atomstroyexport, the &lt;strong&gt;Russian state company&lt;/strong&gt;, and Nuclear Power Corporation of India Limited (NPCIL).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It has a capacity of &lt;strong&gt;6,000 MW of electricity.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The construction of the Kudanukulam Nuclear Power Station began&amp;nbsp;on 31 March 2002.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

